      "title": "Module 1: Foundational Analog and Digital Electronics",
      "subtitle": "Building Blocks of Electronic Systems",
      "content": "Before diving into microcontrollers, a solid grasp of fundamental electronic principles is essential. We start with **Ohm's Law** ($V = I \times R$) and **Kirchhoff's Laws**, which govern how voltage and current behave in circuits. **Resistors**, **capacitors**, and **inductors** are the passive components that embody these laws. Resistors impede current flow, with their resistance measured in Ohms ($\Omega$). Capacitors store energy in an electric field, and their behavior is frequency-dependent, characterized by their capacitance in Farads (F). Inductors store energy in a magnetic field, opposing changes in current, measured in Henries (H).\n\nActive components like **diodes** and **transistors** (BJTs and MOSFETs) are the workhorses for switching and amplification. Diodes allow current flow in one direction, essential for rectification. Transistors act as electronically controlled switches or amplifiers; a small base or gate current/voltage controls a larger current flow between collector-emitter or drain-source. **Operational Amplifiers (Op-Amps)** are versatile integrated circuits used for tasks like amplification, filtering, and signal conditioning. Understanding their ideal behavior (infinite gain, infinite input impedance, zero output impedance) and common configurations like the **inverting** and **non-inverting amplifiers** is crucial.\n\nDigital electronics builds upon these concepts using **Boolean Algebra** and **logic gates** (AND, OR, NOT, XOR). These gates perform logical operations on binary inputs (0s and 1s). Combinational logic circuits, like **adders** (for arithmetic) and **multiplexers** (for data selection), produce outputs solely based on current inputs. Sequential logic circuits, such as **flip-flops** and latches, have memory; their output depends on both current inputs and past states. This introduces the concept of state. Understanding **number systems** (binary, decimal, hexadecimal) is fundamental for interpreting digital data. When analyzing circuits, using tools like **LTspice** for simulation and **multimeters** and **oscilloscopes** in the lab provides practical insights into voltage, current, and waveform behavior. For example, an oscilloscope can reveal unexpected ringing or overshoot on a digital signal transition due to parasitic inductance and capacitance.",
      "resources": [
        {
          "name": "Khan Academy: Electrical Engineering",
          "url": "https://www.khanacademy.org/science/electrical-engineering/ee-circuit-analysis"
        },
        {
          "name": "All About Circuits: Digital",
          "url": "https://www.allaboutcircuits.com/textbook/digital/"
        },
        {
          "name": "TI Design Training: Introduction to Electronics",
          "url": "https://www.ti.com/design-training/training-and-content/introduction-to-electronics.html"
        },
        {
          "name": "Electronics Tutorials: Input/Output",
          "url": "https://www.electronics-tutorials.ws/io/io_2.html"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Module 2: Microcontroller Architecture and Introduction to Registers",
      "subtitle": "The Brains of Embedded Systems",
      "content": "Microcontrollers (MCUs) are specialized integrated circuits designed to control specific tasks in embedded systems. Unlike microprocessors, which require external memory and peripherals, MCUs integrate a **CPU**, **memory**, and **I/O peripherals** onto a single chip. The **CPU** itself consists of the **Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU)** for calculations, the **Control Unit** to direct operations, and a set of **registers**.\n\n**Registers** are small, high-speed storage locations within the CPU used to hold data, instructions, and memory addresses that the CPU is actively working with. Examples include the **Program Counter (PC)**, which holds the address of the next instruction to be executed, and the **Accumulator**, used for arithmetic operations. The speed at which the CPU operates is determined by its **clocking and timing** signals.\n\nMemory in an MCU is typically divided into **RAM** (Random Access Memory) for temporary data storage, **ROM** (Read-Only Memory) or **Flash memory** for program code storage, and sometimes **EEPROM** for non-volatile configuration data. **Memory organization** dictates how data is laid out and accessed, often involving specific **addressing modes**.\n\n**I/O Ports** are the MCU's connection to the outside world. Each port is typically controlled by a set of registers. The **Data Direction Register** (DDR or TRIS register) configures each pin of the port as either an **input** or an **output**. For example, writing a '1' to a specific bit in the DDR might configure the corresponding I/O pin as an output, while writing '0' configures it as an input. The **Port Data Register** (PORT or LAT register) is used to read the state of input pins or to write data to output pins. If a pin is configured as an output, writing a logic HIGH (e.g., 3.3V or 5V) to the PORT register will drive the pin HIGH, and writing a logic LOW will drive it LOW. If it's an input, reading the PORT register will give you the logic level present on the pin.\n\n**Special Function Registers (SFRs)** are a class of registers that control the various peripherals (timers, serial interfaces, analog-to-digital converters, etc.) within the MCU. Each SFR has a specific address and a defined bit layout, where individual bits or groups of bits configure the behavior of a peripheral. For instance, a control register for a timer might have bits to enable the timer, set its prescaler, or select its mode. Understanding the MCU's **Instruction Set Architecture (ISA)** defines the commands the CPU can execute to manipulate data and control peripherals. **Interrupts** are signals that can temporarily halt normal program execution to handle an urgent event, like data arriving on a serial port.",
      "resources": [
        {
          "name": "Microchip: Microcontroller Basics",
          "url": "https://www.microchip.com/en-us/support-and-training/design-tools-and-software/mplab-x-ide/microcontroller-basics"
        },
        {
          "name": "Coursera: Introduction to Microcontrollers",
          "url": "https://www.coursera.org/learn/introduction-to-microcontrollers"
        },
        {
          "name": "Engg Journals: Microcontroller Architecture",
          "url": "https://www.enggjournals.com/download/microcontroller-architecture-and-its-applications.pdf"
        },
        {
