        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Module 3: Embedded C Programming Fundamentals and Register Access",
      "subtitle": "Controlling Hardware with Code",
      "content": "Embedded C programming bridges the gap between abstract software logic and direct hardware control. It extends the standard C language with features and practices tailored for resource-constrained environments. Key to this is understanding **data types** specific to embedded systems, such as `uint8_t`, `int16_t`, etc., which define fixed-size integers crucial for predictable register manipulation.\n\n**Control flow statements** (`if`, `else`, `for`, `while`) manage the program's execution path. However, the most critical operators for hardware interaction are the **bitwise operators**: **AND** (`&`), **OR** (`|`), **XOR** (`^`), **NOT** (`~`), **left shift** (`<<`), and **right shift** (`>>`). These operators allow manipulation of individual bits within registers. For example, to set a specific bit (e.g., bit 3) in a register named `PORTA` to HIGH without affecting other bits, you would use the operation: `PORTA = PORTA | (1 << 3);`. This ORs the current value of `PORTA` with a mask where only bit 3 is set.\n\n**Direct register access** is achieved by treating memory addresses associated with hardware registers as pointers. For instance, if a microcontroller datasheet specifies that the **Data Direction Register** for Port B is at memory address `0x05`, you would declare a pointer: `volatile uint8_t *DDRB_REG = (volatile uint8_t *)0x05;`. The `volatile` keyword is crucial; it tells the compiler that the value at this memory location can change unexpectedly (e.g., due to hardware interrupts or external signals) and that it should not optimize away reads or writes to this address. To configure pin 0 of Port B as an output, you'd write: `*DDRB_REG = *DDRB_REG | (1 << 0);`.\n\n**Macros** are extensively used to define meaningful names for register addresses and bit positions, improving code readability and maintainability. For example: `#define PORTB (*(volatile uint8_t *)0x06)` and `#define PB0 (1 << 0)`. Then, you can write `PORTB = PORTB | PB0;` to set pin 0 of Port B HIGH.\n\n**Basic I/O Port Manipulation** involves setting, clearing, or toggling bits. Setting a bit to HIGH uses the OR operation, clearing to LOW uses the AND operation with a mask of inverted bits (e.g., `PORTA = PORTA & ~(1 << 3);` to clear bit 3), and toggling uses the XOR operation (e.g., `PORTA = PORTA ^ (1 << 3);`). Simple **Timer/Counter** configurations also involve writing specific values to timer registers to set count limits, prescaler values, and operational modes. Understanding how to use an **Integrated Development Environment (IDE)** and **compiler** is vital for writing, building, and debugging this low-level code. A common mistake is forgetting the `volatile` keyword, leading to unexpected behavior as the compiler optimizes away critical register accesses.",
      "resources": [
        {
          "name": "Keil: Writing Embedded C Code",
          "url": "https://www.keil.com/appnotes/files/an137.pdf"
        },
        {
          "name": "Learn C Programming",
          "url": "https://www.learn-c.org/"
        },
        {
          "name": "Embarcados: Introduction to Embedded C",
          "url": "https://www.embarcados.com.br/an-introduction-to-embedded-c-programming/"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silicon Labs: Writing Embedded C Code",
          "url": "https://www.silabs.com/community/mcu/8-bit/knowledge-base/blog.entry.html/2017/08/02/writing_embedded_c_code-nQpQ"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Module 4: Interfacing and Basic Embedded Systems Projects",
      "subtitle": "Bringing It All Together",
      "content": "This module focuses on integrating the electronic fundamentals and programming skills to build functional embedded systems. **I/O interfacing** is the core concept, enabling the microcontroller to interact with external components. For **LEDs and switches**, an LED is typically driven by an output pin through a current-limiting resistor. A switch connected to an input pin, often with a pull-up or pull-down resistor, allows the microcontroller to sense user input. For example, configuring a pin as input, enabling its internal pull-up resistor, and connecting a switch between the pin and ground means reading a HIGH logic level when the switch is open and a LOW when closed.\n\nInterfacing with **sensors** often involves reading analog or digital signals. A temperature sensor might output an analog voltage proportional to temperature, which is read by the microcontroller's **Analog-to-Digital Converter (ADC)**. A digital sensor, like a motion detector, might simply change its output pin's logic level when triggered. Interfacing with **actuators** like buzzers or small motors requires careful consideration of current requirements. Often, a simple microcontroller pin cannot supply enough current, necessitating the use of a transistor driver or a dedicated motor driver IC. For instance, a MOSFET can be used as a switch to control a motor, with the microcontroller pin controlling the MOSFET's gate.\n\nUnderstanding **basic serial communication**, like **UART** (Universal Asynchronous Receiver/Transmitter), is crucial for debugging and inter-device communication. UART uses two pins (TX for transmit, RX for receive) and communicates data serially. Configuration involves setting the baud rate, data bits, parity, and stop bits, often by writing values to specific UART **registers** (e.g., Baud Rate Generator registers, Control registers).\n\n**Project integration** involves combining these elements: writing C code to configure I/O pins, read sensor data, process it, and control actuators. **Debugging embedded systems** is a practical skill that involves using debuggers to step through code, inspect variable values, and monitor register contents in real-time. Alternatively, using serial communication (e.g., sending status messages over UART to a PC's terminal) is a common debugging technique. **Power considerations** are also important; understanding the current draw of the microcontroller and peripherals helps in selecting appropriate power supplies and managing battery life.",
      "resources": [
        {
          "name": "Arduino: Electronics Learning",
          "url": "https://docs.arduino.cc/learn/electronics"
        },
        {
          "name": "Udemy: Embedded Systems Practical Training",
          "url": "https://www.udemy.com/course/embedded-systems-practical-training/"
        },
        {
          "name": "STMicroelectronics: STM32CubeMX",
          "url": "https://www.st.com/en/embedded-software/stm32-cubemx.html"
        },
        {
          "name": "SparkFun: Tutorials",
          "url": "https://www.sparkfun.com/tutorials/categories/2"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
